00:00:20.860 --> 00:00:27.400 align:middle line:84%
>> Hello, I'm Rees Jones,
and welcome to Module 8;

00:00:27.400 --> 00:00:29.230 align:middle line:90%
learning from your inner world.

00:00:29.230 --> 00:00:32.520 align:middle line:90%


00:00:32.520 --> 00:00:34.290 align:middle line:84%
In this module,
I'll be teaching you

00:00:34.290 --> 00:00:37.800 align:middle line:84%
how to bring about scenarios
in your lucid dreams

00:00:37.800 --> 00:00:41.940 align:middle line:84%
that are ripe with
meaning and purpose,

00:00:41.940 --> 00:00:45.840 align:middle line:84%
like recreating traumatic
experiences from your past

00:00:45.840 --> 00:00:48.900 align:middle line:84%
as a way to better come
to terms with them.

00:00:48.900 --> 00:00:52.350 align:middle line:90%


00:00:52.350 --> 00:00:55.800 align:middle line:84%
Upon first hearing this,
it's normal to feel

00:00:55.800 --> 00:00:58.260 align:middle line:90%
a little skeptical.

00:00:58.260 --> 00:01:04.590 align:middle line:84%
You might wonder what good can
dreaming really do for trauma.

00:01:04.590 --> 00:01:06.590 align:middle line:90%
And I hear you.

00:01:06.590 --> 00:01:10.570 align:middle line:84%
This is a perfectly
reasonable response.

00:01:10.570 --> 00:01:12.750 align:middle line:84%
After all, we've
grown up in a society

00:01:12.750 --> 00:01:18.240 align:middle line:84%
that has essentially forgotten
the importance of dreaming.

00:01:18.240 --> 00:01:21.600 align:middle line:84%
In fact, most of us don't
only disregard dreaming,

00:01:21.600 --> 00:01:26.760 align:middle line:84%
but we don't even remember
dreaming in the first place.

00:01:26.760 --> 00:01:29.540 align:middle line:84%
